\section{Summary}
\label{sec:conclusion}
As the sample size of SN Ia rapidly grows, the statistical uncertainties of SN Ia have been
reduced effectively, and the systematical uncertainties have become more and more
important. One of the most important factors causing systematical uncertainties is the
potential evolution of SN (i.e., the possibility of redshift-dependence of
$\alpha$ and $\beta$), which has drawn a lot of attentions in recent years
\cite{Marriner11,Mohlabeng13,WangWang2013a,Shariff15}.

In a latest work \cite{Shariff15}, using the JLA sample, Shariff et al. found
4.6$\sigma$ CL evidence for a significant drop in $\beta$ at redshift $z=0.66$.
Notice that the results of \cite{Shariff15} depend on two particular parameterizations of $\beta$.
To extract more information about SN systematical uncertainties from JLA sample,
we revisit this issue with the redshift tomography method.
To ensure that our results are insensitive to the details of redshift tomography,
we take into account the cases of 3 bins, 4 bins and 5 bins, respectively.
Then we constrain the $\Lambda$CDM model and check the consistence of cosmology-fit results in each bin.
Moreover, in addition to the full JLA sample, we also apply the same technique to various subsamples of JLA,
and then explore which subsample plays a more important role in causing the systematical uncertainties of SN.
So far as we know, the effects of various JLA subsamples on $\beta$'s evolution have not been studied in the past.
Besides, the impacts of time-varying $\beta$ is also studied.

In this work, using the full JLA sample,
we find that the stretch-luminosity parameter $\alpha$ is always consistent with a constant (see Fig~\ref{fig:alpha}).
In contrast, although $\beta$ is still consistent with a constant at low redshift,
it has a significant trend of decreasing, $\sim 3.5\sigma$ CL, at high redshift (see Fig~\ref{fig:beta}).
Since these conclusions hold true for all the cases of 3 bins, 4 bins and 5 bins,
we can conclude that they are insensitive to the details of redshift tomography.
It should be mentioned that,
the evolution behaviors of $\beta$ given by JLA sample
are consistent with the results of some other SN samples \cite{Marriner11,Mohlabeng13},
but are inconsistent with the results of SNLS3 dataset,
which indicates that $\beta$ has a trend of increasing at high redshift \cite{WangWang2013a}.
The reason causing this tension is still unclear and deserves further study.

Moreover, by studying the subsamples of JLA with the same technique,
we find that low-$z$ subsample favors a constant $\beta$;
in contrast, both SDSS and SNLS subsamples favor a decreasing $\beta$ at high redshift (see Fig~\ref{fig:subsamples}).
Besides, compared with SDSS subsample, SNLS subsample prefers a larger decreasing rate of $\beta$ (see Fig~\ref{fig:subsamples}).
Notice that the results of $\beta$ given by SDSS is consistent with the results of \cite{Marriner11},
but the results of $\beta$ given by SNLS subsample is quite different from the results of \cite{WangWang2013a}.
This means that SNLS3 dataset may exists some unknown systematic uncertainties \cite{Betoule2014}.
In addition, although HST subsample only contains 9 data points,
it can slightly slow down the decreasing rate of $\beta$ at high redshift (see Fig~\ref{fig:HST}).
Based on the results of Figs \ref{fig:subsamples} and \ref{fig:HST},
we can conclude that SNLS subsample plays a main role in causing the evolution of $\beta$.

In addition, we also study the impacts of possible redshift-dependence on parameter estimation
using a binned parameterization of $\beta$.
Making use of the full JLA sample only, we find that, compared with a constant
$\beta$, a varying $\beta$ yields a larger bestfit-fit value of $\Omega_{m0}$ , which
is consistent with the conclusion of \cite{Shariff15}. We also compare the cosmological fitting result
of JLA SN data with the result given by the CMB+BAO data. We find that the best-fit
value of $\Omega_{m0}$ for the constant $\beta$ case is more close to the
result given by CMB+BAO data, which is different from the case of SNLS3 sample \cite{WLZ14}.
However, $\Omega_{m0}$'s result for the varying $\beta$ case
is still consistent with the result for the constant $\beta$ case,
as well as the result given by other observations, at $1\sigma$ CL (see Fig \ref{fig:Om0}).

In this paper, we only consider the simplest $\Lambda$CDM model.
In addition to the $\Lambda$CDM model,
many other DE models \cite{Li2004,Chevallier01,Linder03} are also favored by current cosmological observations.
It is of interest to study the effects of varying $\beta$ on parameter estimation
in other dark energy models~\cite{Zlatev1999,Caldwell2002,Li2004,WZ2008,WZX2008,LiLiWang2009a,LiLiWang2009b,Huang2009,WLL10,WLL11}.
This will be done in future works.

Moreover, there are some other factors that can also cause the systematical uncertainties of SN,
such as the evolution of intrinsic scatter $\sigma_{int}$ \cite{Kim11,Marriner11},
the impacts of weak lensing \cite{Wang2000,WCM12},
and the impacts of different light-curve fitters \cite{Kessler09,Bengochea11,Hu15a,Hu15b,Hu15c}.
It is interesting to study the effects of these factors on cosmology-fits.
We will investigate these issues in future.

